<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 94 / Weekend Money: Finance Week
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS
Italian prime minister Silvio Berlusconi, whose seven-month-old government
was toppled after a revolt by his Northern League coalition partner,
resigned rather than face defeat in a no-confidence drive in parliament.
President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro is left with the delicate decision of finding
a new government or dissolving parliament.
The Home Office has asked the Court of Appeal to review the convictions of
the four original Guinness trial defendants because of allegations that
material evidence was withheld from the defence.
Britain's current account balance of payments moved into surplus for the
first time in 7 1/2 years in the third quarter.
John Major said that he would make peace with the Conservative party's
rebels over Europe only on his own terms.
The UK's 6m part-time workers are to have most of the statutory employment
rights of those in full-time jobs, the government announced. The decision
represents a climbdown for the government which two weeks ago vetoed a draft
European Union directive on part-time workers.
The Halifax Building Society plans to cut buildings insurance premiums by an
average of 20 per cent from January 1.
London Life Association, part of London Life Group, has been fined Pounds
50,000 by Imro, the self-regulatory body for the fund management industry,
for rule breaches that left client money at risk.
Serious breaches of regulatory rules emerged in the announcement of fines
imposed by Lautro, the life insurance watchdog, on two friendly societies -
Homeowners and Ideal Benefit.
Cruise operator Cunard blamed sub-contractors for delays in completing a
Pounds 30m refit of the liner Queen Elizabeth 2, which resulted in 500
passengers being turned away from its Christmas cruise. Cunard said
passengers unable to travel on this cruise could take two others next year -
should they want to.
The government will receive nearly Pounds 960m from the sale of British
Coal's mining assets. This emerged as details were announced of the sale of
the south Wales region for Pounds 94.5m.
Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, decided not to refer the
proposed acquisition by the Halifax Building Society of Leeds Permanent
Building Society to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
US investors have provided the bulk of new capital committed to Lloyd's of
London for next year, partly filling the hole left by exiting Names -
individuals whose assets traditionally have supported the insurance market.
COMPANIES
The first contested take-over bid in the UK utility sector got under way as
Northern Electric, the regional power company for the north-east of England,
rejected a Pounds 1.2bn offer from Trafalgar House.
Trafalgar House decided to offer a Pounds 20 rebate to each of Northern
Electric's 1.3m customers. This, it claimed, was at the prompting of the
electricity industry regulator, Professor Stephen Littlechild. Labour
questioned whether Littlechild had shown 'proper conduct' in asking
Trafalgar representatives what customers would gain from the bid.
Shares in troubled UK developer Stanhope Properties were suspended after the
breakdown of negotiations with banks owed Pounds 140m.
Unilever's problems with its revolutionary new detergents appeared to have
disrupted the orderly succession to the group's top job. The company
announced a postponement of previously announced boardroom changes amid
mounting evidence that Persil Power and Omo Power, the detergents launched
this spring, have failed to meet their targets.
UK bioscience company Zeneca is to pay up to Dollars 485m (Pounds 310m) for
Salick Healthcare, a Los Angeles-based operator of specialist cancer
centres.
Mercury Communications, the UK's second largest public telecommunications
operator, cut international call charges for its largest users in reaction
to intensifying competition.
SG Warburg has beaten other investment banks, including Morgan Stanley, the
bank with which it planned to merge until last week, in the competition to
advise the government on the privatisation of Railtrack.
A Pounds 1.5bn offer to buy the St Martins Property group, the leading
property business owned by the Kuwaiti government, has been made by Barings,
the London merchant bank, on behalf of an investment consortium.
Mars, the privately owned US confectionery and pet foods group, has launched
a review of the bulk of its Dollars 1bn (Pounds 640m) world-wide
advertising, in response to Maurice Saatchi's removal from the board of
advertising group Saatchi &amp; Saatchi.
Intel, the world's biggest computer chip-maker, offered to replace free of
charge the flawed Pentium microprocessors that are the 'brains' of millions
of high performance personal computers.
Shares in East Midlands Electricity rose by 5 per cent after the group
announced substantially better than expected interim results and a
surprisingly large dividend increase.
Peter Ward is to quit as chief executive of Rolls-Royce Motors, which has
signed a collaboration agreement with BMW of Germany. The move is believed
to reflect a disagreement with the parent Vickers board on the future of the
luxury car builder.
Robert Montague finally conceded defeat in his attempt to stave off
bankruptcy, resigning as chief executive of Tiphook, the trailer rental
company he founded 16 years ago.
UK security printer De La Rue's Pounds 682m offer for Portals was accepted
by the specialist paper-maker's board.
Shareholders in British Assets Trust have approved a capital re-organisation
but raised questions about the trust's relationship with Ivory &amp; Sime, its
fund manager.
Private investors have taken up fewer than a sixth of the shares available
to them in RJB Mining's sale of shares to fund the purchase of British
Coal's English regions.
MARKETS
Mexico's stock market fell heavily and short-term interest rates rose
sharply following Tuesday's 15 per cent devaluation of the peso, pulling
down other Latin American markets. The currency was driven to new lows and
the Mexican government was forced to float the peso - abandoning its fiscal
policy of keeping the currency in a specified target zone.
Sales of uncut diamonds remain near record levels, but the market is still
in turmoil and cutters continue to complain about lack of profitability.
The US stock market attempted a tentative year-end rally as the Dow Jones
broke through the 3,800 mark on Wednesday for the first time since November
18.
The present bull market in base metals probably will end in the third
quarter of 1995, according to analysts at the Merrill Lynch financial
services group.
The world's two major nutmeg producers, Indonesia and Grenada, have
suspended negotiations on a new joint marketing agreement amid concerns
about the involvement of a European marketing company. They will resume
their discussions in March.
