<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Financial Planning): Revenue's error -
Briefcase
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
In May 1993 I was made redundant and my redundancy money was taxed via PAYE
(the excess over Pounds 30,000). In June, I applied for and received a tax
rebate as I had no intention of working for the rest of the tax year, nor
claiming unemployment benefit. In August 1994, I completed a return for the
tax year to April 1994. Recently, I received another tax rebate with my
notice of assessment. It appears that the IR did not take into account the
first tax rebate from June last year.
Am I obliged to point out this error, which is in my favour? If I do not,
what happens if or when the error is discovered?
Wilful failure to point out the over-repayment could constitute a criminal
offence under the Theft Act. The procedure for recovering over-repayments of
tax is set out in section 30 of the Taxes Management Act 1970, as amended.
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All enquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
