<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Financial Planning): Terminating a Tessa -
Briefcase
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
My wife and I have each substantial investments in self-select personal
equity plans and Tessas. Our wills provide for leaving our possessions to
each other. As far as our investments in Peps are concerned, which of the
following options are open to our executors:
1. To terminate the respective Pep, sell the investments and transfer the
proceeds to the beneficiary?
2. To terminate the Pep, not sell the underlying shareholdings but merely
transfer them to the beneficiary?
3. Not to terminate the Pep or the investments but to transfer the Pep (plus
underlying investments) to the Pep of the survivor, where the investments
will continue on a tax-free basis?
With Tessas, will these have to be terminated? And will the interest
credited up to the date of death be paid gross without deduction of tax,
even though the stipulated period of five years from the start of the Tessa
was not completed at the time of death?
The tax-exempt status of a Pep will terminate automatically on the death of
the plan-holder so the third option is not available to you. In theory,
options 1 and 2 both are possible, although it should be noted that the
transfer of investments or cash will be made by the plan manager to the
personal representatives of the deceased.
Many plans, however, operate on the basis that the underlying investments
will be sold automatically on death, so it is important to check the
position with the particular plan manager concerned.
Tessas also terminate automatically on death and the proceeds are paid gross
by virtue of S326A(2) ICTA 1988, providing all other conditions have been
met. (Reply by Andrew White).
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All enquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
