<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Financial Planning): Charity and the law -
Briefcase
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Following the death of my grandfather a few years ago, a sum of money was
raised and put into a trust. This money is now being used for educational
and cultural purposes.
The trustees, of whom I am one, have been considering whether to seek
charitable status. I have read the relevant literature produced by the
Charities Commission. But I need to do further reading on the powers and
duties of trustees. Could you refer me to the standard works covering this
area of the law?
The Charities Commission produces a series of leaflets and we would
recommend Responsibility of Charity Trustees (CC3) and Investment of
Charitable Funds: Basic Principles (CC14). If these are not sufficient, the
commission also publishes a video: Charity Trustees: The Crucial Guide to
Trusteeship.
For more detailed information, you might like to consider Tolley's Charities
Manual, published by Tolley Publishing Company, 2 Addiscombe Road, Croydon
CR9 5AF as being the most comprehensive work on all aspects of the subject.
(Reply by Andrew White of Gordon Leighton &amp; Co.).
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All enquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
