<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Financial Planning): When a gift is taxable -
Briefcase
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
I own a half share in a plot of land leased to a petrol company, on which it
built a petrol station 30 years ago. Eight years of the lease remain.
If I were to give my share (value Pounds 70,000) to my two nieces, would I
be liable to pay capital gains tax immediately on valuation? Or am I correct
in thinking that this can be put off so long as my nieces do not sell the
property? And is there any top limit to the value of a gift?
You can make gifts of any value without inheritance tax being payable if you
survive for seven years from the date of giving. There is no limit to
potentially-exempt transfers, which become fully exempt after seven years.
You are correct in your concern over CGT. You are gifting an investment and
CGT could be payable. It is not possible to defer tax if your nieces do not
sell the property, as it is not possible to obtain hold-over relief on the
gift of an investment.
If there is likely to be a large CGT liability, you could consider putting
the assets into a discretionary trust as a gift for the benefit of your two
nieces, so that hold-over relief is available.
While this gift would fall within your nil rate band, this band would become
available again in full after seven years. Within the next 10 years, the
assets could be transferred out of the trust to your nieces, or the trust
could be changed so that it became a life interest trust; IHT could be
avoided in this way.
I suggest, however, that you take legal advice if you wish to pursue this
matter further and contact your accountant regarding the likely CGT which
could be involved. (Reply by Barry Stillerman of accountant Stoy Hayward).
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All enquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
