<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 94 / Weekend Money: Permanent interest-bearing shares
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Pibs are the closest you can get to holding ordinary shares in a building
society. They are fixed interest securities with no redemption date - so
your capital cannot be guaranteed. You can realise your investment only by
selling them on the open market - with the chance of capital gain or loss.
They provide a relatively high yield, as the table shows. This is partly
because a building society is theoretically not obliged to pay out if doing
so would drive it into loss. Also, the market is relatively small and the
shares are not always easy to buy and sell.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                        Coupon     Issue  Minimum    Price*    Yield*
                                   price
Stock                (gross %)       (p)    (Pds)       (p) (gross %)
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Birmingham Midshires     9.375   100.165    1,000    90        10.411
Bradford &amp; Bingley      11.625   100.129   10,000   113.75     10.220
Bradford &amp; Bingley      13       100.2     10,000   126.25     10.297
Bristol &amp; West          13.375   100.338    1,000   127.75     10.470
Britannia               13       100.423    1,000   124        10.484
Cheltenham &amp; Gloucs     11.75    100.962   50,000   116.75     10.064
Coventry                12.125   100.749    1,000   115.25     10.505
First National          11.75    100.247   10,000   103        11.408
