<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Companies): Battle of Trafalgar begins - Bids
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES and CHRIS PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The first take-over of a privatised utility began this week with Trafalgar
House's Pounds 1.25bn bid for Northern Electric, writes David Lascelles. It
should provide an interesting test for what could be a wave of take-overs
and mergers in the power sector.
Northern was quick to reject the bid as coming from 'a financially
challenged conglomerate', a reference to Trafalgar's troubled recent
history. It also said the bid consisted of 'paper of uncertain value'.
These, though, are the clashes one expects in a contested bid. Northern's
private shareholders (and there are 120,000 with fewer than 1,000 each) can
afford to wait many weeks, even months, for the smoke to clear before having
to make firm decisions.
The bid is worth Pounds 10.48 a share in cash, or slightly more in a mixture
of cash and convertible shares. The offer price is not far enough above the
price of the shares themselves (Pounds 10.06 at last night's close) to
guarantee success, but there is a long way to go.
A big question is whether the bid will be referred to the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission where, being the first of its kind, its fate would be
hard to predict. Here, Professor Stephen Littlechild, the electricity
regulator, could play an important role.
He said this week that the bid raised a number of issues which he would like
to examine. At his prompting, Trafalgar has offered Pounds 20 already to
each of Northern's customers to make it more acceptable.
The government itself owns a blocking 'golden share' but this expires on
March 31 and is unlikely to play a big role in the bid (which could not be
completed much before then, anyway). Politically, however, Labour might try
to portray this as yet another bonanza for privatisation stockholders, which
could be another reason for sending it to the MMC.
Whether the debate touches on the merits of the bid itself remains to be
seen. Trafalgar is thought to be making the sally to get its hands on
Northern's strong cash flow; it has nothing special to offer managerially.
On the other hand, financial analysts feel Northern's management could do
with a bit of gingering up.
Portals, the specialist paper supplier, this week succumbed at last to the
overtures from De La Rue and accepted a Pounds 682m offer from the world's
biggest commercial bank-note printer, writes Chris Price. The move will give
De La Rue control of one of its main paper suppliers and boost its access to
Portals' customer contacts among the world's central banks.
Jeremy Marshall, De La Rue's chief executive, said: 'With Portals' paper
manufacturing and our printing expertise, the enlarged group will be able to
enjoy greater technological focus, particularly in anti-counterfeiting, and
a strengthening of customer relationships.'
The deal is expected to dilute De La Rue earnings slightly for the year to
March 31 1995, be neutral in 1995-96, and enhance earnings the year after.
De La Rue will pay Pounds 403m in cash for Portals, with the rest being
covered by a fully underwritten issue of new shares. The offer of nine
shares and Pounds 124 in cash for every 20 Portals shares values the latter
at Pounds 10.50 per share.
Portals' shareholders will be offered a full cash alternative of Pounds
10.11 1/2 a share and a mix-and-match facility.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
