<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (UK Equities - Winners and Losers): Famine
follows a market feast - It has been hard to avoid losing money this year.
David Wighton looks at some sectors that bucked the trend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After three years of plenty came the famine. Between the beginning of 1991
and the end of 1993, UK share prices rose by more than 60 per cent. It was
hard not to make money in the stock market. In 1994, it was hard not to lose
it.
Even those shares that did well showed dramatically lower gains than in the
previous year. In 1993, four members of the FT-SE 100 index more than
doubled. In 1994, only one rose by more than 20 per cent.
The fate of particular sectors also contrasted sharply with 1993, reflecting
the (for the UK) unusual character of the economic recovery. While
industrial profits have risen sharply, companies closest to the consumer
have struggled, particularly those related to the still stagnant housing
market. So, general retailers and building merchants languished, while
engineers and paper and packaging companies did much better.
The strong showing of the latter sector illustrated the importance of
another of the year's trends - rising prices for raw materials. Many
manufacturing companies saw such costs increase alarmingly but had
difficulty raising their own prices in the new, low-inflation world. As a
result, many had their margins squeezed. But paper and packaging companies -
including Bowater, the sector's largest constituent - managed to pass on
most of the increased costs to their customers.
De La Rue, the bank-note printer, also had a good year and gave the sector
another boost before Christmas with its bid for Portals, which makes paper
for the notes. Portals' shares took the top spot in the FT-SE Mid-250 index
(the companies ranked from 101 to 350 in terms of stock market value).
One of the companies responsible for other manufacturers' higher raw
material costs is British Steel, which is surging back into profit helped by
a string of price increases. Metal ore prices also rose, pushing the mineral
extraction sector up the table.
The oil price improved over the year, too, helping the exploration and
production companies, while the integrated companies like BP also saw
recovery in their chemicals operations. BP capped a good year by regaining
its position as the UK's most valuable company.
While British Steel's top placing represents the continuation of a strong
run - it was the Footsie number two last year - others have seen a sharp
reversal in fortunes. In 1993, shares in leading supermarket chains tumbled
on fears of an escalating price war. But Sainsbury and Tesco seem to have
held off the discounters' assault this year and the shares have staged a
strong comeback. Tesco, which was six from bottom in the Footsie in 1993, is
fifth from the top this year, with Asda fourth.
The pharmaceuticals companies also had a much better year, with SmithKline
Beecham enjoying a particularly good run. Passing them on the way down were
the commercial property companies, which won prizes in 1993 but languished
near the bottom of the class this year.
Another fallen star is HSBC (the Hongkong and Midland Bank group) which, on
top of the general fall in world bond markets, has been hit by the slump in
the Hong Kong stock market. So, too, has Cable &amp; Wireless, which gets the
bulk of its profits from its stake in Hongkong Telecom; while C&amp;W's Mercury
subsidiary has seen profits dip due to competition from BT and other new
entrants into the UK telecom market.
Given the sharply higher profits being reported by UK insurance companies,
the poor performance of their shares might seem odd. Both Guardian Royal
Exchange and General Accident were in the last 10 of the Footsie, and the
sector was second from bottom.
As usual, the stock market is looking ahead. Investors in the sector are
worried about the impact of low-cost direct insurance operators on the
established companies, while life and pensions business is expected to be
hit by regulatory changes. At the same time, the companies' investment
returns will be hit by lower share and bond prices.
Shares in BAT Industries, which constitute the bulk of the tobacco sector,
were affected because of the group's insurance companies as well as the
regulatory and legal threats to its US tobacco business. But the regional
electricity companies had another good year thanks to a friendly regulatory
review of Trafalgar House's bid for Northern Electric. Eastern took the
sixth spot in the Footsie.
</TEXT>
