<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 94 / Weekend Money (Markets): Brewers droop and spirits are
lower, too - Drink / But prospects for the industry over the next year are
far from gloomy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RODERICK ORAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Given the volume of drinks sent, received and consumed by the City at this
time of year, it is no surprise that the beer and spirits indices normally
outperform the market in November and December. After all, the upsurge of
activity must be benefitting somebody's bottom line, personal or corporate.
This year, though, they have not - for only the second time since the 1987
crash. Since November 1, the breweries sector of the FT-SE Actuaries
All-Share index is down 1.5 per cent against the market and the spirits
sector is down 3.4 per cent.
The problem with spirits was clear from the recent results of Guinness,
Grand Metropolitan and Allied Domecq, the three largest spirits groups in
the world. Slow economic recovery in many of their country markets makes it
very hard for them to raise volume and prices.
Analysts also had some specific niggles with Grand Met and Allied when
results fell short of forecasts, and many downgraded their estimates for
this year.
The case of the drooping beer index is a little harder to fathom. For the
first time since the recession, brewers and pub owners expressed some modest
confidence as they announced their results over the past month. Profits
matched forecasts and analysts nudged up their estimates.
An unexpected excise duty increase in chancellor Kenneth Clarke's
mini-Budget soured investor sentiment, but the index's weakness is more
relative than absolute. Brewers' earnings will grow this year, but probably
at a slower rate than earnings of the overall market. Yet, the sector is
still on a prospective market rating and is, relatively, a touch too
expensive.
All the medium-term trends for brewers and publicans are still at work: beer
volume will be down about 1 per cent this year; premium brands and cask ales
are growing strongly; people are drinking less in pubs and more at home;
trade discounting is deep and widespread; and pubs that push food and
amenities are increasing their trade.
Some of those factors came through strongly in the results. Good summer
weather in parts of the UK stimulated beer sales and many brewers said the
upturn continued during the autumn.
Premium brands proved particularly strong for Whitbread. Its sales of
Heineken Export, Stella Artois, Boddingtons and Murphy's showed percentage
growth in the teens for the six months to end-August.
The best news on pubs came from Scottish &amp; Newcastle, which has reaped more
than expected from its Pounds 703m acquisition last year of the Chef &amp;
Brewer chain. But its plans to spend even more on developing its various pub
formats, mirrored by many other companies' plans, raises an awkward question
for the sector. Is too much money chasing the same development sites and pub
themes?
'Its quite frightening that everybody seems to have read the same Henley
Centre report on eating out,' says one analyst. If any of the forecasts are
slightly wrong, a lot of people will be caught out.
Differentiating its own brands of, say, food-serving pubs from those of a
rival will be a challenge for any of the brewers. Whitbread is acknowledged
as the best at the game, and Bass the one with the most still to do to
segment its estate into brands.
Picking a beer stock is a matter of taste. Whitbread has the proven record
in premium beers and pub branding, but its price reflects that. Scottish &amp;
Newcastle offers growth from its pubs and leisure interests. Bass is the
biggest gamble, while Greene King is the regional brewer recovering from the
lowest base.
Similarly, the choice varies among the spirits stocks, although none looks
alluring given their modest earnings outlook. But when volumes and prices do
begin to rise, perhaps late next year, the effect on profits will be
dramatic.
One leading analyst estimates that a 1 per cent rise in prices adds Pounds
20m to the pre-tax profits of Guinness, while 1 per cent on volume adds
Pounds 13m.
Of the three companies, Guinness has the best array of premium brands should
drinkers start to move back up market. Moreover, its beer profits exceed
those of Bass, Scottish &amp; Newcastle and Whitbread combined.
Allied Domecq, hurt by a Mexican downturn in its latest results, will take
time to derive benefits from its purchase of Domecq, a leading Spanish and
Latin American spirits producer. But, of the three, it is the most narrowly
focused on spirits.
Grand Met's spirits division, IDV, needs a long list of minor repairs and
renovations, judging by the omnibus re-structuring charge the group has just
taken. And it is still trying to plug the gap left by losing the Absolut
vodka franchise in the US.
For any investor spoilt by the choice of drink stocks, perhaps the best
approach would be to try the products of each company over the next 10 days
 -in moderation, of course.
</TEXT>
<XX>
