<PROFILE>_AN-ELXAIACKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941224
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 DEC 94 / World Stock Markets (Europe): Cyclicals more mixed as
Frankfurt eases on session
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Market Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Political hopes continued to move Italy, but its hard currency neighbours
made a more sedate approach to the Christmas holiday, writes Our Market
Staff.
FRANKFURT suspended its recent enthusiasm for front line cyclicals, and
chemicals, carmakers and engineers were mixed as the Dax index eased 6.64 to
2,094.01 on the session, up 1.1 per cent on the week.
Turnover fell from DM5.2bn to DM4bn. In the post bourse, shares edged higher
with Wall Street, the Ibis-indicated Dax closing at 2,100.98. In cyclicals,
Bayer fell DM4 to DM360.10 Mannesmann rose DM5 to DM420; Ms Barbara Altmann
at B Metzler in Frankfurt said that some foreign, judicious profit taking
had been balanced by 'window dressing'.
The latter might explain why Allianz moved from a loss of DM6 on the session
to a gain of DM10 at DM2,510 after hours. Otherwise, financials were weak on
unrealised hopes for a bond market revival.
PARIS, as a market, moved quietly towards Christmas Eve with the CAC-40
index off 2.2 at 1,949.85, but 1.3 per cent higher on the week.
However, there was more cheer at the level of individual stocks. On Thursday
night, L'Oreal said that its Paravision International unit had sold about
300 films to Canal Plus, the French pay-TV channel. Yesterday L'Oreal rose
FFr26 to FFr1,145 and Canal Plus FFr11 to FFr898  - suggesting, somehow,
that both sides had got the better of the deal.
Meanwhile, Valeo said that it would have 75 per cent of a joint venture with
Siemens to produce systems and electric motors for car heaters and air
conditioners, and the French company's shares rose FFr3 to FFr257.
MILAN continued higher as hopes rose that the country would avoid early
elections which might postpone action on the budget deficit and possibly
bring higher interest rates. The Comit index picked up 1.70 to 629.00, with
the weakness of the lira still prompting foreigners to buy. The index had
risen by 3.8 per cent during the course of a highly charged week on the
political front which saw the resignation of the prime minister, Mr Silvio
Berlusconi on Thursday.
Olivetti, popular with foreign investors, rose L87 or 4.5 per cent to
L2,040, but analysts were unable to point to any news to account for the
rise.
Other blue chips found strong demand taking Fiat L136 higher to L6,024 and
Telecom Italia up L75 to L4,193.
Credito Italiano slipped L17 to L1,678 amid concern that it might relaunch a
bid for Credito Romagnolo. Rolo, for which a group headed by Cariplo is also
bidding, rose L151 to L19,073.
ZURICH featured a 3.7 per cent fall in Holderbank as the cement producer,
which has companies in Mexico and in other Latin American countries, fell
prey to the Mexican financial crisis. The SMI index finished 1.2 higher at
2,651.0for a 1.8 per cent rise on the week.
One leading domestic bank was said to be a major seller in Holderbank, which
also saw foreign sell orders. The shares fell SFr38 to SFr1,003, although
some analysts commented that the fall seemed to have been overdone.
UBS was again seen as a buyer of its own shares, which have been under
pressure recently, and the bearers rose SFr16 to SFr1,111.
AMSTERDAM finished with modest falls after a shortened session and the AEX
index lost 0.95 to 414.40. It was still 1.5 per cent ahead on the week.
Among chemicals shares, Akzo was up 40 cents to Fl 198.10, helped by
positive comments about higher 1995 and 1996 sales. DSM was Fl 1 higher at
Fl 139.30.
Other leading shares were uninspired with Philips down 20 cents to Fl 52.30
and Royal Dutch off 60 cents to Fl 188.30. Heineken lost Fl 3 to Fl 261.50
on profit-taking after recent gains, while other food and drink issues were
mixed.
MADRID staged a technical recovery in low volume, the general index rising
1.68 to 292.88, 1.7 per cent lower on the week in turnover of just
Pta13.4bn, close to the lowest measure of market activity this year.
STOCKHOLM edged lower with the market's lacklustre performance exacerbated
by an early close on the debt market and higher government bill rates and
bond yields. The Affarsvarlden General index eased 0.5 to 1471.1.
MoDo, the forestry group, rose SKr5 to SKr346 after a large block trade in
the stock led to speculation that its fellow paper products group, SCA, had
sold some of its large holding.
HELSINKI revived after news that a pay deal had averted strikes in the
forestry and paper industries. The Hex index rose 19.0 to 1,813.7, a
fraction better on the week, with Repola up FM4 at FM84.
Written and edited by William Cochrane and Michael Morgan
