FT  24 DEC 94 / Insurance repayment ordered
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Farmers, the US insurance group owned by BAT Industries of the UK, was
ordered by California's insurance commissioner yesterday to repay Dollars
183m (Pounds 117m) of premiums to policyholders under the state's
controversial Proposition 103 law. The 1988 law, which required insurers to
roll back premiums and pay rebates to Californian holders of car and other
insurance policies, was recently upheld by the state's supreme court, in
spite of opposition from the US insurance industry.
The Farmers directive comes a month after Mr John Garamendi, the Californian
insurance commissioner, ordered 28 other US insurers to make a total of
Dollars 1.25bn in Proposition 103 repayments. In a separate action, Mr
Garamendi ordered Farmers to end its policy of issuing earthquake insurance
policies with deductibles of up to 25 per cent.
