<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 94 / International Company News: Eastern Air poised to emerge
from bankruptcy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Eastern Air Lines, once one of the biggest US airlines but long defunct, may
start flying again following a US court's approval of its plan to emerge
from bankruptcy.
The New York court approved a scheme announced in September under which
Eastern will emerge from chapter 11 bankruptcy protection by paying off its
creditors, so clearing the way for a new Eastern Air Lines.
Under the plan, unsecured creditors with claims of Dollars 100,000 or less -
mostly ticket holders, employees and vendors - will get 11 cents for each
dollar's worth of debt on Dollars 200m worth of allowed claims. About 150
unsecured creditors with claims of more than Dollars 100,000 will receive
several distributions over a period of 12-18 months. These will probably
total 9 cents to 14 cents in the dollar, but could possibly reach 17 cents.
Allowable claims total Dollars 1.1bn.
The plan also provides for full payment of secured creditors and reconfirms
all prior payments made to various creditors since the shutdown.
Eastern went into bankruptcy in March 1989 amid a bitter power struggle
between its unions and its then chairman, Mr Frank Lorenzo. It was grounded
in 1991.
</TEXT>
