<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Investors build on Wednesday
rally in Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
In spite of further turmoil on Latin American debt and equity markets and
declines in Treasury prices, leading US stocks firmed yesterday as investors
looked to build on Wednesday's strong rally, writes Patrick Harverson in New
York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 13.12 at 3,814.92. The
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 performed less well, ending only
0.06 higher at 459.67, while the American SE composite slipped 0.41 to
427.52 and the Nasdaq composite rose 2.22 to 739.34. New York SE volume was
340.3m shares.
The market opened in an upbeat mood following the previous day's 35-point
gain which pushed the Dow above the 3,800 level for the first time since
mid-November.
The day's main economic news - an upward revision in third-quarter gross
domestic product growth from 3.9 per cent to 4.0 per cent - had little
impact on stocks. Although bond prices declined, this too had little effect
on the market, which appeared to be in the middle of establishing a solid
late-December rally.
The positive mood, however, was dampened by events in Latin America, where
most bond and stock markets were rocked by the news that the Mexican
government had abandoned plans to try and keep the value of the peso within
a particular trading range. From now on, it will let the currency float
freely against the dollar.
The announcement prompted heavy selling of Mexican ADRs (American Depositary
Receipts). Telefonos de Mexico fell Dollars 4 3/8 to Dollars 40 5/8 in
volume of 17m shares, the construction giant Grupo Tribasa by Dollars 2 3/4
to Dollars 19 5/8 , the media conglomerate Grupo Televisa by Dollars 3 3/8
to Dollars 32 1/8 and the bank Grupo Financiero by Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars
8 7/8 . Selling spread to other Latin American ADRs, with Telecom Argentina
falling Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 47 5/8 .
The Latin American turmoil upset US banks which do a lot of business in the
region. Citicorp fell Dollars 2 to Dollars 41 1/4 , Bank of Boston Dollars
3/4 to Dollars 26 3/4 and JP Morgan Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 55 1/4 . In
contrast, Bankers Trust rose Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 56 5/8 after the bank
agreed to pay a relatively modest fine of Dollars 10m to government
regulators to settle charges relating to its sale of derivatives to the
Gibson Greetings company.
On the Nasdaq market, Borland International declined Dollars  7/8 to Dollars
6 5/8 after the technology group said revenues in the current quarter would
be substantially lower than a year ago.
Canada
Toronto finished slightly higher as markets showed signs of winding down for
the holiday season. The TSE 300 composite index added 7.10 at 4,182.72 and
advances outscored falls by 399 to 321 after volume of 48.1m shares valued
at CDollars 527m. Ten of the 14 sub-indices rose, including golds.
</TEXT>
