<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 94 / Property: The new realism - Sellers are willing to accept
lower prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After an exceptionally quiet autumn, the property investment market is
stirring. The Pounds 1.5bn unsolicited offer for St Martins Property Group,
owned by the Kuwaiti government, is the most obvious sign of life.
But other, less glamorous, deals completed over the past few weeks could be
more significant indications of the overall health of the market.
Properties which have been on sale for months have finally been sold. This
is not because enthusiastic buyers are offering better prices, but because
sellers are now willing to accept the prices on offer.
Land Securities' sale last week of its Milton Gate office block in the City
of London looks like a case of this new realism among sellers.
AP Fonden, the Swedish national pension fund, paid Pounds 76.5m for the
property. While that is above the property's March valuation, it is much
below the original asking price - thought to be about Pounds 85m.
'We thought we were going to see a lot of activity this autumn but it never
happened,' said Mr John Slade of Richard Ellis, the surveyors. 'Expectations
on the part of vendors were clearly too high and have had to come down to
more realistic levels.'
Similarly, Friends Provident's purchase of London Capital Holdings from
Citibank followed an unsuccessful attempt to float the company on the stock
market in May.
Citibank withdrew the planned flotation because stock market investors were
not willing to pay a price close to the company's Pounds 240m net asset
value. While the details of the Friends Provident deal were not disclosed,
it seems likely that the life insurer has paid less than Citibank
anticipated in the summer.
Realism on the part of sellers bodes well. A healthy property investment
market relies on some common ground between buyers and sellers.
The snag is that the weight of UK institutional money trying to get into the
property market has dissipated over the past year. According to Hillier
Parker, the surveyors, institutional cash totalling Pounds 10bn was waiting
to be invested in property at the peak of the market in March. Since then
interest has fallen. The top funds now have only about one-third the amount
available.
The drift of institutions away from property partly reflects a realisation
that the outlook is not as rosy as it seemed.
According to forecasts by the London Business School, capital values will
rise by just 2.6 per cent next year against about 9 per cent this year.
Moreover, property has outpaced both bonds and equities in 1994. Even
without committing additional funds, the weighting of most life and pension
funds to property has risen through this year.
Funds have been drawing breath after the frenetic activity of the first half
of the year, but that will change when 1995 asset allocations are decided,'
said Mr Philip Nelson of Nelson Bakewell, the surveyors. 'I sense that the
investment market is unsticking.'
AP Fonden's latest acquisition also underlines that foreign investment has
become a permanent feature of the central London property market.
The inflow of overseas funds this year - at about Pounds 1.8bn - is nowhere
near the Pounds 3bn-plus annual totals of the late 1980s. But such huge
inflows were caused by an extraordinary mixture of sky-high confidence and
deregulation in countries such as Sweden and Japan.
The evidence of the past four years suggests that central London might, in a
normal year, expect Pounds 1.5bn - Pounds 2bn net investment from overseas.
'The UK is now seen by international funds as an established long-term
destination for investment in property,' said Mr Peter Evans, head of
research at DTZ Debenham Thorpe, the surveyors.
Having done well from acquisitions made at the trough of the market in
1991-92, German open-ended funds are particularly keen buyers.
Overseas buyers appear to be interested in different types of property than
UK funds. Milton Gate - sold on a yield of 8.85 per cent - was typical of
the kind of over-rented building foreign investors are keen to buy. In
contrast, UK fund managers are willing to acquire properties on low yields
if they can scent rental growth. Yields of 5-6 per cent are not uncommon in
the City.
With money flowing in from overseas, steady interest from domestic
institutions and some agreement among buyers and sellers, a healthier flow
of investment deals is in prospect for the new year.
However, old hands warn that the market may never recapture its heady past.
Sir Brian Goswell, head of Healey &amp; Baker's City office, said: 'The market
is slow in relation to the late 1980s but activity is normal from a
long-term point of view. The difference is that agency fees are much lower
than in the past. The feel-good factor among agents is simply not there.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6552 Subdividers and Developers, Ex Cemeteries.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
