<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 94 / Rules tightened on financial controls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY, Accountancy Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Listed companies will have to make a statement in their accounts next year
describing their internal financial controls or face censure by the Stock
Exchange.
The new rules were published yesterday by a working group on internal
control convened at the request of the Cadbury committee on the financial
aspects of corporate governance.
Mr Paul Rutteman, chairman of the group, which includes representatives of
the Hundred Group of Finance Directors, said: 'The focus on the
effectiveness of a company's system of internal control will add to
shareholder confidence in UK listed companies.'
The Cadbury committee, which issued its report at the end of 1992, advised
companies to provide a statement of internal controls in their accounts,
which led to the creation of the working party.
Companies are not forced to comply, but any quoted business that does not
must note in its accounts that it fails to meet this requirement of the
Cadbury code on pain of reprimand from the Stock Exchange.
Failures in internal financial controls have been identified as the key
element in several corporate failures in recent years.
Effective internal controls include regular training in financial
instruments, authorisation limits, segregation of duties and the production
of accurate and regular business statistics.
The guidance requires that directors.
State that they are responsible for internal financial controls.
Explain that such a system is no guarantee against loss or misstatement.
Describe the key procedures of financial control in the company.
Confirm that they have reviewed the effectiveness of the controls.
Comment where weaknesses in systems have resulted in 'material losses,
contingencies or uncertainties' which require disclosure.
The guidance comes into force from January 1, although there are
transitional arrangements which will allow some companies to report on
systems in place after July 1.
</TEXT>
