<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 94 / Cheap exports infuriate dairies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Milk Marque, the farmers' dairy co-operative, sold cut-price milk to Ireland
last week after causing a furore in November when it raised prices in
England and Wales by as much as 20 per cent.
The exports have caused an outcry in the dairy industry where higher prices
forced some companies to close processing plants. Dairies are angry that
surplus milk has been made available to Irish cheesemakers at about 3p per
litre below the cost of supply on the daily UK wholesale market.
'It is infuriating for companies which are locked into high-priced annual
contracts. British consumers are clearly being ripped off by this abuse of
monopoly power,' said Mr Neil Davidson, president of the Dairy Industry
Federation.
Dairies and supermarkets raised consumer prices for milk by between 1p and
2p per pint in response to higher wholesale prices when the Pounds 3.3bn
market was deregulated in November.
Mr Andrew Dare, chief executive of Milk Marque, said the export sales were
required to cope with an emergency breakdown of Unigate's large processing
plant at Chard, Somerset, and the annual shutdown of several other plants.
The current milk surplus is unusual and is partly caused by the mild weather
which encourages cows to produce more milk - farmers are producing 2.6 per
cent more than their quotas - and partly by farmers' attempts to cash in on
high prices.
Mr Dare said supply and demand in the run-up to Christmas were always
difficult to forecast.
Milk Marque's sales system forced dairy companies to bid for yearly supplies
at a range of prices. Some companies' bids were scaled back in November
because of a shortage of supply at that time.
Milk Marque has also put a reserve price on the spot market for daily
wholesale sales to stop prices falling below 22p per litre. Sales to Ireland
are understood to have been at 19p per litre.
</TEXT>
