<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 94 / Ministers back reform of EU cash transfers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government has given broad support for a European Commission plan to
make it cheaper and quicker for small businesses to transfer money across
borders.
The proposed legislation has been vigorously opposed by European banking
organisations, which argue that legislation could disrupt efforts by larger
banks to improve transfer arrangements and mean that smaller banks would no
longer offer transfer services.
Apacs, the UK organisation which represents payment clearing services, said
yesterday that it would now try to ensure that the commission's directive
would be flexible enough not to inhibit competition.
Mr Anthony Nelson, Treasury minister, said that while British banks
generally did well compared with other European banking sectors in terms of
providing transfer services in good time, they were ranked much lower in
terms of expense.
He said: 'We need higher standards and much more observance of standards.
The average time taken to transfer a payment - which a study for the
commission showed had increased to 4.8 days in 1994 - is wholly
unsatisfactory in the single market.'
The French government has indicated that pursuing the proposals would be a
priority for its presidency, although the UK government believes that the
target of reaching a common position on the proposals by April is 'very
optimistic'.
The measures put forward by the commission would ban double-charging - where
banks charge customers for receiving cash as well as for sending it.
It would mean that banks would have to refund the charge where the transfer
was not completed, unless another organisation accepted responsibility.
They would also have to ensure that money should be credited to the
recipient's account within six working days, unless the customer and
originating bank agreed it could take longer.
The government will be looking in detail at elements which include the
proposals for refunds if the transfer is not completed; that interest should
be paid if a transfer is completed late; and that administrative charges
should be limited to those that would apply in a domestic credit transfer.
Apacs expressed some concern that the draft directive appeared to apply to
high-value as well as to low-value payments. The original intention had been
to limit the plans to transfers of under Ecu10,000 (Pounds 7,894).
</TEXT>
