<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 94 / Scots economy reported to be slipping back
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Scottish economy, which outperformed all other UK regions during the
recession, has begun to slip back in the recovery, according to Scotland's
main economic research organisation.
The Fraser of Allander Institute at Strathclyde University says that
although Scottish manufacturing output has risen faster than that of the UK
as a whole since 1992, this is almost entirely due to rapid expansion by the
electronics sector.
Without the electronics sector manufacturing output would have declined.
'The recovery in Scottish manufacturing is much more narrowly based than
manufacturing in the UK,' the institute says.
Its latest quarterly bulletin points out that official statistics for output
by the production and construction industries in the second quarter of 1994
(the latest avail-able) show a fall of 1.1 per cent in Scotland compared
with a rise of 1.8 per cent in the UK.
In the year to the second quarter of 1994, output in production and
construction grew by 3.3 per cent against 3.4 per cent in the UK.
Over the two years from the second quarter of 1992 production in Scotland
grew by 6 per cent compared with 8.1 per cent for the UK.
Manufacturing output in Scotland grew by 7.5 per cent over the two years,
outpacing the UK's 5.1 per cent. However Scotland's advantage was almost
entirely due to a rise of 64.2 per cent in the electrical and instrument
engineering (electronics) sector, compared with a rise of 19.4 per cent in
the UK.
Only two other industrial sectors in Scotland - oil processing and chemicals
and fibres - showed growth in the two-year period, while mechanical
engineering, and metals and metal goods showed sharp declines.
Quarterly Economic Bulletin. Fraser of Allander Institute. Curran Building.
100 Cathedral Street, Glasgow G4 0LN. Pounds 15.
</TEXT>
