<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 94 / Christmas bonus for Gingrich
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Santa Claus, in the guise of one of Mr Rupert Murdoch's publishers, has come
early for Congressman Newt Gingrich, next Speaker of the US House of
Representatives. But the Christmas present - a book advance said to be worth
Dollars 4m (Pounds 2.5m) - has been instantly transformed into a distinctly
unseasonal row.
The congressman's office yesterday confirmed a Washington Post report that
Mr Gingrich would sign a contract with Harper-Collins, the New York
publishing subsidiary of Mr Murdoch's News Corporation, for two books. He
would write one about his own political philosophy and edit the other, a
political anthology.
The Post put the advance at Dollars 4m and an aide to Mr Gingrich said:
'That's about the figure I've heard.' Whatever the precise sum, it far
exceeds the congressman's previous literary earnings, such as the modest
Dollars 15,000 commission he received last year to write an as yet
unpublished novel.
Not surprisingly, the White House jumped all over the story yesterday. Ms
Dee Dee Myers, in her last day on the job as press secretary, said the deal
'raises some very important questions', such as the 'size and timing' of the
payment.
Mr James Carville, President Bill Clinton's campaign manager in 1992, was
typically more to the point. 'This is the first guy who tried to cash in
before he was sworn in. Are you sure he's not going to give it to some
orphanage?' - a wicked allusion to one of the next Speaker's solutions for
America's welfare problems. Mr Murdoch, in Beijing, said he had 'no
knowledge' of the deal.
</TEXT>
