<DATE>941223
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 DEC 94 / World Trade News: Canadian tax deepens culture row with US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A dispute between the US and Canada over efforts to protect Canadian
magazines, television services and cultural institutions deepened yesterday
when Ottawa imposed an 80 per cent excise tax on advertising revenues from
magazines compiled in the US and beamed electronically to Canadian printing
plants.
The new tax is payable by the printer or local distributor.
The move was specifically directed against Time Warner, the US entertainment
and publishing group which took advantage of a loophole in Canadian trade
laws last year to combine Canadian advertising and US editorial content in a
low-cost local edition of Sports Illustrated. Other US magazines, which
already dominate Canadian news stands, have been closely watching the Sports
Illustrated experiment.
US trade officials say Canada's most recent moves on cultural protectionism
represent 'a disturbing trend'. Mr Mickey Kantor, the US trade
representative, is expected to announce that he will work closely with the
US industry to consider all options, including retaliation.
Ottawa secured an exemption for the cultural sector from the 1989 US-Canada
free trade agreement. But the US is allowed to retaliate against any new
protective measures to an equivalent commercial value.
Washington is also angered by a Canadian regulatory ruling this year to
withdraw a licence granted to Country Music Television (CMT), a US cable-TV
channel two-thirds owned by Westinghouse Electric. Cable operators are due
to replace the US channel with a Canadian country music service on January
1.
CMT, which has been available in Canada for about 10 years and is carried to
2m Canadian homes, plans to ask the US trade representative to file a
complaint under section 301 of the US international trade law. Although they
voraciously tune into US television stations and read US publications,
Canadians are highly sensitive to any perceived threat to their own cultural
institutions.
'The Americans simply see it as a product and entertainment,' Ms Catherine
Keachie, director of the Canadian Magazine Publishers Association said
yesterday. 'Canadians are quite clear that we have to have our own books,
films and magazines to maintain a unique culture.'
About half of Canada's 1,400 periodicals made a profit in 1992. 'It is not a
matter of profitability . . . but of survival,' Mr Michel Dupuy, heritage
minister, said yesterday.
The government also unveiled plans to impose a consumer levy on blank audio
tapes. The proceeds will be distributed to musicians, singers and other
artists to compensate for lost sales due to copying of tapes and records.
</TEXT>
